Approximately 9% of samples/rows having missing fileds in each dataset. To cleanse the missing data, we must understand the information encoded by the variables and the necessary assumptions for modeling.
Even though the corrupt samples account for only 1/10th of each dataset and imputation could introduce bias, the naive method of dropping rows with missing fields is not appropriate here as we have to generate a prediction for each delivery_id in the testing data.

We want to verify if time-series modeling and associated data cleansing steps are necessary for this dataset. As there are hundreds/thousands of unique stores in each market, it is hard to visualize all of them, hence observing the distribution of timestamps in the ordered dataframe can provide some information about the sampling rate.

As there is geographical information in the form of store_id and market_id, and studies show the impact of location on delivery services, we explore the quality of these variables first ( Abousaeidi et al. 2015, Hubner et al. 2016).

We will clean the driver and order information variables: total_onshift_drivers, total_busy_drivers and total_outstanding_orders.
We will impute the median value for each market. The median value avoids being skewed due to outliers and market specific imputation can further reduce data cleaning bias.

# Impute driver info in training data
markets = unique(frame_hist_data[is.na(frame_hist_data$total_onshift_drivers), 'market_id'])

  frame_hist_data$total_onshift_drivers[is.na(frame_hist_data$total_onshift_drivers)] = 
    median(frame_hist_data[frame_hist_data$market_id == market_id_, 'total_onshift_drivers'], na.rm = T)
  frame_hist_data$total_busy_drivers[is.na(frame_hist_data$total_busy_drivers)] =

Section 2

Feature Engineering and Modeling

We will now define the modeling problem and required features and begin with the simple paradigm of linear regression assuming that the delivery time is a linear function of the available independent variables, defined as:
\(Y = f( X_i \beta)+ \epsilon_i\)
Where, \(Y\) is the dependent variable i.e. delivery time, \(X\) represents the independent variables, \(\beta\) are the coefficients and \(\epsilon\) the error terms.

We are required to predict the total delivery duration in seconds, which is defined as:
\(Total\ Delivery\ Duration\ (seconds) = Actual\ Delivery\ Time - Order\ Created \ Time\)

Which in turn can be redefined as a prediction problem for the actual delivery time:
\(Actual\ Delivery\ Time = Order\ Created \ Time + Order\ Preparation\ Time + Store\ to\ Customer\ Time\)

\(Store\ to\ Customer\ Time = f(Available\ drivers + Outstanding\ Orders + Subtotal + Driving\ Time)\)

Here we do not have information on order preparation time and store to customer time, however we have a proxy for the latter: estimated_store_to_consumer_driving_duration.
Note: Ideally, order price should not be an influencing factor, however it is known that drivers try to maximize the order amount while minimizing driving distance for better profits.

We will create a new duration variable total_delivery_duration. This will allow us to observe the distribution of delivery duration and patterns for modeling.
\(Total\ Delivery\ Duration\ (seconds) = Actual\ Delivery\ Time - Order\ Created \ Time\)

# Calculate total delivery duration
frame_hist_data$total_delivery_duration = as.integer(difftime(frame_hist_data$actual_delivery_time, 
                                                              frame_hist_data$created_at,  units = 'secs'))

We will now select the necessary features and create the linear regression model.
We will avoid any transformations as the dependent variable has to be in seconds.
We will use a random 80:20 split and 10-fold cross validation to estimate in two different ways the generalizability of the model.
